headline: Palantir rallies after bumper quarter fueled by US defense spending
summary: Shares of Palantir Technologies jumped 6.9% in early trading on Tuesday as investors bet on the company's military-grade AI tools and services after ​it reported a surge in quarterly sales, boosted by rising U.S. defense spending.  Denver, Colorado-based Palantir ‌is on track to add about $24.4 billion to its market value at the current price of $158, if gains hold.  The company, founded by tech billionaire Peter Thiel and with the CIA as one of its early backers, said on Monday that revenue derived from the U.S. government jumped 66% in the fourth quarter to $570 million, helping lift total sales to $1.41 billion, above analysts' estimate of $1.33 billion.

headline: Gold Buyers, This Isn’t the 1970s
summary: A popular stat cited by goldbugs to show how well the metal has held its value is that an ounce could buy “a decent men’s suit” in ancient times (a toga, presumably) and still can today.  Later that decade it could have paid for the polyester duds John Travolta sported in “Saturday Night Fever.”  If incoming Federal Reserve Chair Kevin Warsh isn’t quite the sound-money guy some believe, could momentum resume?
